# Intuition & approach
Many solutions count number of days before the given month in runtime. But this value is fixed, so can be precalculated and stored in an array, instead of number of days per month. We can even create a second array to store number of days passed for leap years to avoid having an additional `if` in runtime.

By merging the arrays into an array of arrays, we basically create a look-up table, where the required value is directly accessible by first index being an indicator if the year is leap or not, and the second index being a number of month preceding the given month.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(1)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
static const array<array<int, 12>, 2> days{{{{0, 31, 59, 90, 120, 151, 181, 212, 243, 273, 304, 334}}, {{0, 31, 60, 91, 121, 152, 182, 213, 244, 274, 305, 335}}}};

class Solution {
public:
    int dayOfYear(string date) {
        int year = stoi(date.substr(0, 4));
        int month = stoi(date.substr(5, 2));
        int day = stoi(date.substr(8, 2));

        return days[isLeap(year)][month - 1] + day;
    }

private:
    bool isLeap(int year) {
        if (year % 100 == 0) {
            return year % 400 == 0;
        }
        return year % 4 == 0;
    }
};
```

